Alexis Atkins, who was nine when her father was taken into custody, has visited her father in jail since his incarceration. 

The 29-year-old labelled the Court's decision 'really quite surreal,' reported The Advertiser.

'Obviously, it’s really exciting and what we’ve been waiting 20 years for. I think the biggest thing I’m looking forward to is being able to spend time with him without there being time constraints or security guards watching over us, Mrs Atkins said. 

Compelling evidence was provided that aspects of Ms Cheney's autopsy lacked substantiation, and Ms Mancock recanted on evidence he had provided at Keogh's trial, the court heard.

In September Flinders University Professor Anthony Thomas told the Court that evidence was either incomplete or in disarray, reported The Advertiser.

Professor Thomas also drew the Court's attention to the swelling of Ms Cheney's face, which may have indicated she suffered an allergic reaction to an anti-histamine drug she had taken prior to her death. 

